The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Sunday, May 16, 2004 				 PNB pushes for pension fund
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								New Delhi, May 15: State-run Punjab National Bank today said it has applied to the finance ministry for setting up a fund that will enable the bank to retail pension products. 																								Officials said while the bank would hold a 37 per cent stake in the proposed fund, Principal Asset Management Company would have a 26 per cent stake, Vijaya Bank 12 per cent and Berger Paints 25 per cent.																								We have applied to the pension regulator which has been set-up under the aegis of the finance ministry, said S.S. Kohli, chairman and managing director of PNB.																								The New Delhi-based bank, which is one of the larger banks after State Bank of India, also said its net profit for the last financial year stood at 31.6 per cent to Rs 1108.69 crore, up from Rs 842 crore a year ago.																								The bank also announced a dividend of Rs 4 a share of face value Rs 10. We have sought RBIs permission to allow us pay a 40 per cent dividend to our shareholders, said Kohli.																								Gross income during the year stood at Rs 9,647 crore, up 10.4 per cent from Rs 8,735 crore in the previous fiscal. Advances during the year reported flat at 17 per cent to Rs 47,225 crore from Rs 40,228 crore a year ago.																								Total business rose 16.5 per cent to Rs 1,35,141 crore during the last financial year from Rs 1,16,041 crore in the previous financial year.																								The bank also formed a joint venture with the US-based life insurer Principal Financial Group to form PNB Principal Asset Management Company. 
